"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860551","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-03-15","<p>The available information on the number of people on Universal Credit by conditionality regime is published and can be accessed at:</p><p><a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/</a>.</p><p>Guidance on how to extract the information required can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started.html" target="_blank">https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started.html</a></p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-03-15T09:03:37.33Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860551/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860551/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860551/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-03-12","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate her Department has made of the number of people who are subject to in-work conditionality under universal credit.","false","Biography information for Margaret Greenwood","Wirral West","Margaret Greenwood","131908"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860552","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-03-15","<p>Work coaches engage at a personal and individual level with all of or our claimants and are committed to tailoring the support that we give, and any conditionality requirements to the specific circumstances of the individual.</p><p>The Department’s internal analysis indicates that there will be around 1 million claimants in work on Universal Credit, receiving support when Universal Credit is fully rolled out.</p><p> </p><p>This internal analysis is derived from the Department’s INFORM and Policy Simulation models.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-03-15T16:23:41.247Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860552/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860552/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860552/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-03-12","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate she has made of the number of people who will be subject to in-work conditionality once the roll-out of universal credit is complete.","false","Biography information for Margaret Greenwood","Wirral West","Margaret Greenwood","131909"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860553","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-03-15","<p>Claimants will not be required to make repayment of their SMI loan until their property is sold or transferred. We anticipate that, in the vast majority of cases, there will be a charge placed on the property. This means that the recovery process will usually be handled via a solicitor dealing with the sale or transfer rather than directly with the claimant. Where there is insufficient equity to repay in full, claimants will not be pursued for the balance.</p><p> </p><p>Recovery of mortgage interest loans will be the responsibility of the Department for Work and Pensions (DWP) Debt Management who will be putting in place a new and bespoke Support for Mortgage Interest (SMI) Loan Management unit. DWP currently deals with elderly and vulnerable customers every day, and there are no plans to deal with elderly or vulnerable SMI claimants any differently.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2018-03-15T13:55:43.483Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860553/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860553/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860553/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-03-12","Mortgages: Debt Collection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, which organisation will be responsible for debt recovery from mortgage interest loans and what guidance will be provided to that organisation on responding to elderly and vulnerable claimants.","false","Biography information for Margaret Greenwood","Wirral West","Margaret Greenwood","131910"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860554","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-03-16","<p>The Resources and Waste Strategy will be published this year.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2018-03-16T12:47:19.177Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860554/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860554/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860554/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-03-12","Waste Disposal","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, when the Government plans to publish its Resources and Waste Strategy for 2018.","false","Biography information for Daniel Kawczynski","Shrewsbury and Atcham","Daniel Kawczynski","131911"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860555","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-03-15","<p>Products containing palm oil must be labelled as such – the vegetable oil ingredient of food must now indicate the vegetable origin of the oil.</p><p>See Annex VII part A 7-8 of the 1169/2011 Regulation on the provision of food information to consumers for more information:</p><p><a href="https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/en/ALL/?uri=CELEX%3A32011R1169" target="_blank">https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/en/ALL/?uri=CELEX%3A32011R1169</a></p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-03-15T12:08:59.543Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860555/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860555/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860555/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-03-12","Palm Oil: Labelling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if he will make it his policy that all products containing palm oil should be labelled as such to enable consumers to decide whether they wish to buy products containing that ingredient.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","131912"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860556","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-03-15","<p>In 2006, Defra published a study into the environmental impacts of a number of commodities, including palm oil.</p><p> </p><p>In 2012, Defra published the UK Statement on the Sustainable Production of Palm Oil which was signed by trade associations, NGOs and Government, and aimed to achieve 100% sourcing of credibly certified sustainable palm oil. The final report in February 2017 reported that by 2015 either 87% or 108% of UK palm oil imports were supported by Roundtable for Sustainable Palm Oil (RSPO) certification, depending on the trade data source used.</p><p> </p><p>Defra is committed to supporting implementation of deforestation free supply chains for key commodities, including palm oil. We are signatory to the Amsterdam Declarations, have endorsed the New York Declaration on Forests and are a member of the Tropical Forest Alliance 2020.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2018-03-15T12:04:57.88Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860556/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860556/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860556/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-03-12","Palm Oil","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment he has made of the effect of palm oil production on wildlife and the environment in palm oil producing countries; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","131913"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860557","Treasury","false","2018-03-15","<p>Following the Aspire exit HMRC has let contracts in relation to Managed Desktop Service (MDS), Managed Print Service (MPS), Bulk Scanning and Bulk Printing. As part of the phased exit HMRC also entered into new agreements with former Aspire providers and novated over 100 sub-contracts that were previously managed by our suppliers. The savings were calculated through the use of a detailed model taking account of the impacts of all of HMRC’s Aspire exit activities and using a baseline of 2014/15.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2018-03-15T15:44:07.613Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860557/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860557/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860557/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-03-12","Revenue and Customs: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 27 February 2018 to Question 128292, on Revenue and Customs: ICT, which contracts the HMRC has let and taken on as part of the Aspire exit; and how the £200 million a year by 2020-21 figure referred to in that Answer was calculated.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","131914"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860558","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-03-20","<p>Government is committed to increasing the quality and quantity of social action opportunities available to young people. The below table outlines the main funding pots and programmes that have been established to provide these opportunities:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>2013</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Live programmes/funds</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Centre for Social Action Innovation Fund</p></td><td><p>Uniformed Youth Social Action Fund</p></td><td><p>National Youth Social Action Fund</p></td><td><p>National Citizen Service</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Local Youth Social Action Fund</p></td><td><p>#iwill fund</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p>European Voluntary Service (EU funded)</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><strong> </strong></p><p>These funds and programmes are not specifically designed to increase the number of full time social action opportunities available, and as such, we do not collect data on the duration of the social action activities provided.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2018-03-20T17:40:21.6Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860558/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860558/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860558/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-03-12","Young People: Voluntary Work","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, which youth full-time social action programmes have received statutory funding in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","131915"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860559","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-03-20","<p>The recently published Review of Full Time Social Action by Young People considered the legal status of young people who could be recorded as NEET (Not in Education, Employment or Training) while taking part in full time social action.</p><p> </p><p>The Government will publish its response to the Review’s report in due course.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2018-03-20T17:38:01.847Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860559/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860559/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860559/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-03-12","Voluntary Work","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, whether he plans to change the status of full-time volunteers from not being in education, employment or training.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","131916"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860560","Home Office","false","2018-03-16","<p>In October 2017, Government announced that it would change the level of financial support paid to all potential victims of modern slavery, using the methodology that determines the subsistence rates paid to asylum seekers to ensure that individuals with comparable living needs receive the same level of support, regardless of their immigration status. All individuals who access support provided by the Victim Care Contract are entitled to receive subsistence payments.</p><p>The subsistence rates for victims of modern slavery are provided to cover the essential living needs of potential victims of modern slavery, including food, toiletries, clothing and other essential needs. When considering the level of these rates, the essential needs of potential victims were assessed to be comparable to the needs of asylum seekers, as both cohorts of individuals also receive accommodation and utilities on top of their subsistence payments. This is why the tested and established methodology that has been developed to measure the level of subsistence for asylum seekers will be adopted to measure the level of subsistence for potential victims of modern slavery.</p><p>Within this policy, dependent children will receive a higher level of subsistence than they currently receive, and pregnant victims will receive an additional payment of £300. The most vulnerable individuals in NRM support will therefore receive a higher level of financial support following these changes. The policy for subsistence rates also includes the ability for individuals or their support providers to apply for further funding if there is a clear need for victims to receive more financial support to meet their essential living needs</p><p>All victims will continue to receive dedicated support tailored to their unique needs as victims of modern slavery. There will be no reduction in the total amount of money spent supporting victims as funding will be reinvested in supporting victims for longer following their conclusive decision. Government has announced that it is trebling the period of move on support for confirmed victims, increasing this period from 14 days to 45 days, to ensure that victims are able to transition into their longer term communities.</p><p>We are working with the Salvation Army and the Independent Anti Slavery Commissioner to ensure that the implementation of this change is as smooth as possible.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2018-03-16T17:46:59.753Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860560/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860560/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860560/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-03-12","Slavery","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many victims of modern slavery will potentially be affected by the proposed reduction in weekly subsistence payments.","false","Biography information for Anne Marie Morris","Newton Abbot","Anne Marie Morris","131917"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860561","Home Office","false","2018-03-15","<p>Tackling modern slavery and human trafficking is a priority for this Government. The Home Office has ensured that sufficient resources are available within the Modern Slavery Unit to support the delivery of the Modern Slavery Strategy. The Modern Slavery Unit has a budget of £1.5 million for financial year 2017/18 which mainly relates to staff costs.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2018-03-15T17:35:56.92Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860561/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860561/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860561/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-03-12","Home Office: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many staff are employed full time in the Modern Slavery Unit; and what estimate she has made of the annual cost to the public purse of those staff.","false","Biography information for Anne Marie Morris","Newton Abbot","Anne Marie Morris","131918"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860562","Home Office","false","2018-03-16","<p>The Departments financial allocation to the Office of the Independent Anti-Slavery Commissioner was £500,000 in 2015/16, and £575,000 in both 2016/17 and 2017/18.</p><p>Further information about the income and expenditure of the Office of the Independent Anti- Slavery Commissioner is detailed in his annual reports 2015/16 and 2016/17.</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/559571/IASC_Annual_Report_WebReadyFinal.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/559571/IASC_Annual_Report_WebReadyFinal.pdf</a></p><p><a href="http://www.antislaverycommissioner.co.uk/media/1164/iasc_annual-report-16-17-web.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.antislaverycommissioner.co.uk/media/1164/iasc_annual-report-16-17-web.pdf</a></p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2018-03-16T17:42:10.537Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860562/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860562/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860562/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-03-12","Independent Anti-slavery Commissioner","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the annual Government allocation to the Office of the Independent Anti-Slavery Commissioner was in (a) 2015-16, (b) 2016-17, and (c) 2017-18; and what proportion of the Commissioner’s total expenditure this represents in each of those years.","false","Biography information for Anne Marie Morris","Newton Abbot","Anne Marie Morris","131919"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860563","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-03-14","<p>Occupational, personal and public service pension schemes are defined in section 1 of the Pension Schemes Act 1993.</p><p> </p><p>A public service pension scheme is an occupational pension scheme established by or under an enactment, the Royal prerogative or a Royal charter, unlike other occupational pension schemes which are set up under trust.</p><p> </p><p>Pension and tax laws may prescribe certain minimum or maximum requirements regarding the benefits that a pension scheme may provide. Beyond that, the type, level and eligibility criteria for benefits due under the scheme are a matter for the sponsoring employer. Details will be contained in the scheme rules or, in the case of public service schemes, the relevant legislation.</p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman",,"2018-03-14T17:33:12.98Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860563/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860563/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860563/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-03-12","Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how his Department defines whether a pension scheme is (a) private and (b) public in calculating benefits eligibility.","false","Biography information for Hywel Williams","Arfon","Hywel Williams","131920"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860564","Treasury","false","2018-03-14","<p>Further to my answer of Parliamentary Question 131221, the UKSPF will support organisations in all parts of the UK to achieve sustainable inclusive growth based on our modern industrial strategy</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2018-03-14T12:25:23.133Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860564/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860564/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860564/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-03-12","EU Grants and Loans: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether organisations in Scotland will be able to access funding from the UK Shared Prosperity Fund.","false","Biography information for Luke Graham","Ochil and South Perthshire","Luke Graham","131921"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860565","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2018-03-19","<p>We are seeking a deep and special partnership with the European Union. Our relationship with the European Union's agencies and bodies upon exit will be evaluated on this basis.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Prior to any decisions on establishing new UK-level bodies, the Government will, however, always look to minimise disruption and costs, which will include considering alternative options. In most cases we anticipate that repatriated EU functions can be absorbed by departments and existing public bodies.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>We will continue to plan for a range of scenarios and be ready to take any necessary steps to ensure that we are ready for exit day.</p><p> </p>","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker",,"2018-03-19T11:26:09.997Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860565/answer","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860565/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860565/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2018-03-12","Regulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what estimate he has made of the number of new regulatory bodies which will be required once the UK leaves the EU; and what the role of each such body will be.","false","Biography information for Phil Wilson","Sedgefield","Phil Wilson","131922"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860566","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-03-19","<p>The Government has no plans to undertake a council tax revaluation.</p>","Richmond (Yorks)","Rishi Sunak",,"2018-03-19T16:10:00.41Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860566/answer","Biography information for Rishi Sunak","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860566/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860566/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-03-12","Council Tax: Valuation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, when his Department plans to review the banding of domestic properties for the purpose of collecting council tax.","false","Biography information for Mike Hill","Hartlepool","Mike Hill","131923"
