"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860614","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","false","2018-03-15","<p>The Commission will examine levels of turnout in the pilot areas at the 2018 elections as part of its statutory evaluation of the Voter ID pilots. This will not include an analysis of the marked registers but will involve the collection of detailed turnout data for 2018 and for previous years with comparable polls, noting that levels of turnout do vary across different years and so it will not necessarily be possible to attribute any changes in turnout to the pilot alone.</p>","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson",,"2018-03-15T11:04:16.19Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860614/answer","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860614/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860614/answer",,,,,"36","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","2018-03-12","Local Government: Elections","1","House of Commons","To ask the hon. Member for Houghton and Sunderland South, representing the Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission, in respect of the areas where Voter ID pilots are being carried out this spring, and where the Commission plans to evaluate those pilots, what studies of the marked registers from the 2018 local elections will be carried out to understand the effect of such trials on levels of turnout.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","131971"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860615","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","false","2018-03-15","<p>As part of its statutory evaluation of the Voter ID pilots, the Commission will be carrying out public opinion research which should provide some insight into the impact on different demographic groups. Data will also be collected directly from polling stations on the numbers of electors unable to vote owing to the ID requirements.</p><p>The Commission does not plan to examine the marked registers as part of its evaluation. The electoral registers do not hold demographic information on electors and the Commission would not be able to evaluate reliably any differential demographic impacts by this route.</p>","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson",,"2018-03-15T11:06:01.44Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860615/answer","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860615/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860615/answer",,,,,"36","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","2018-03-12","Local Government: Elections","1","House of Commons","To ask the hon. Member for Houghton and Sunderland South, representing the Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission, in respect of the areas where Voter ID pilots are being carried out this spring, and where the Commission plans to evaluate those pilots, what studies of the marked registers from the 2018 local elections will be carried out to understand the differential effect of such trials on levels of turnout between different ethnic groups.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","131972"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860617","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","false","2018-03-15","<p>The Commission’s statutory evaluation of the Voter ID pilots will include a survey of all polling station staff in each pilot area, in order to gather information on their experiences of practically administering the ID requirement on the day. The Commission will also interview the Returning Officers and electoral administrators in each pilot area.</p>","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson",,"2018-03-15T11:06:54.733Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860617/answer","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860617/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860617/answer",,,,,"36","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","2018-03-12","Elections: Proof of Identity","1","House of Commons","To ask the hon. Member for Houghton and Sunderland South, representing the Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission, in respect of the areas where Voter ID pilots are being carried out this spring, and where the Commission plans to evaluate those pilots, what steps the Commission is taking to ensure that interviews are carried out not only with electoral registration officers and returning officers but also with people who work for the day as presiding officers in respect of individual polling stations and have personal face-to-face experience of difficulties that electors encounter in those pilot areas.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","131974"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860618","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","false","2018-03-15","<p>The Commission’s statutory evaluation of the Voter ID pilots will include a survey of all polling station staff in each pilot area, in order to gather information on their experiences of practically administering the ID requirement on the day. All of the polling station staff will be encouraged to respond to the survey.</p><p>The Commission will also seek feedback from a wide range of interested groups as part of its evaluation. This will include civil society organisations able to offer insights into how different elements of the pilots could have presented challenges, and delivered benefits, to specific groups of people.</p>","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson",,"2018-03-15T11:08:29.84Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860618/answer","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860618/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860618/answer",,,,,"36","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","2018-03-12","Elections: Proof of Identity","1","House of Commons","To ask the hon. Member for Houghton and Sunderland South, representing the Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission, in respect of the areas where Voter ID pilots are being carried out this spring, and where the Commission plans to evaluate those pilots, what steps the Commission is taking to ensure that a representative group of those people who work for the day as presiding officers in respect of individual polling stations who are representative not only the demography of the area but also the particular challenges which have been identified by civil society groups are interviewed.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","131975"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860619","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-03-15","<p>Our air quality monitoring networks are kept under review to ensure they continue to deliver the UK’s requirements for reporting, evidence and supporting our policy needs. There are currently no plans to expand the particle numbers and concentrations network.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2018-03-15T11:59:14.187Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860619/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860619/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860619/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-03-12","Air Pollution: Monitoring","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, pursuant to his Answer to of 30 January 2018 to Question 12548, on monitoring of PM1, if he will ensure that more sites in the Particulate Numbers and Concentrations Network monitor PMs of less than 2.5.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","131976"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860620","Department for International Trade","false","2018-03-15","<p>I can confirm the goods have now been exported. At the time these items were presented for export we remained satisfied that the licence complied with the Consolidated Criteria.</p>","Beverley and Holderness","Graham Stuart",,"2018-03-15T15:13:32.937Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860620/answer","Biography information for Graham Stuart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860620/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860620/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2018-03-12","Electronic Surveillance: Honduras","1","House of Commons","Pursuant to the Answer of 8 March 2018 to Question 130861, on Honduras: Electronic Surveillance, if the surveillance equipment has been exported from the UK to Honduras.","false","Biography information for Lloyd Russell-Moyle","Brighton, Kemptown","Lloyd Russell-Moyle","131977"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860621","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-04-19","<p>Waste incineration sites are required to continuously monitor emissions of total particulate matter (TPM) in line with the requirements of the European Industrial Emissions Directive. TPM includes PMs of less than 2.5 (PM<sub>2.5</sub>) as well as other sizes. Therefore there is no need to monitor specifically for PM<sub>2.5</sub>. Furthermore there is no commercially available equipment for the continuous monitoring of PM<sub>2.5</sub>.</p><p> </p><p>This approach is further supported by the fact that applicants for new incinerators are required to model PM<sub>2.5</sub> emissions to air by assuming a worst-case scenario that all of the TPM emitted is PM<sub>2.5</sub>. This is a very precautionary approach as in practice TPM will be a mixture of sizes, and so the true impact will be less.</p><p> </p><p>The Environment Agency will only issue a permit for an incinerator if it is satisfied that emissions of particulate matter will not have a significant impact on the environment under the worst-case scenario.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2018-04-19T10:59:07.187Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860621/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860621/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860621/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-03-12","Incinerators","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if he will require operators of waste incineration sites to monitor emissions of particulate matters of less than 2.5.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","131978"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860622","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-03-22","<p>Ofgem considers interconnectors’ contribution to welfare as part of their assessment for regulatory approval.</p><p>The first round of projects that received regulatory approval from Ofgem showed GB consumer welfare benefits of up to £12 billion over their 25 year regulated lifetimes.</p><p>The second round of projects that received regulatory approval from Ofgem (GridLink, NeuConnect, and NorthConnect) showed GB consumer welfare benefits of over £7 billion over their lifetimes.</p><p>The full details of Ofgem’s assessments for these projects, and a small number of other projects which have been assessed separately, can be found at</p><p><a href="https://www.ofgem.gov.uk/electricity/transmission-networks/electricity-interconnectors" target="_blank">https://www.ofgem.gov.uk/electricity/transmission-networks/electricity-interconnectors</a>.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2018-03-22T11:27:58.137Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860622/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860622/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860622/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-03-12","Electricity Interconnectors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether he has made an assessment of the effect of increased electricity interconnection on welfare.","false","Biography information for David T. C. Davies","Monmouth","David T. C. Davies","131979"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860623","Cabinet Office","false","2018-03-28","<p>Burdens on smaller regulators were raised in the <em>Regulatory Futures Review</em> with regard to the implementation of the 2016 Enterprise Act’s provisions for independent scrutiny of the impact on business of regulatory changes. The Public Accounts Committee also recommended an approach to assessing impacts (Recommendation 6 of its 2016-17 report on Better Regulation – HC 487). In light of both reports ministers modified the Better Regulation System to make it more proportionate for both departments and regulators as reflected in the <em>Interim Guidance on the Better Regulation</em> <em>Framework</em> published by the Department of Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy on 22 February 2018.</p>","Norwich North","Chloe Smith","133348","2018-03-28T15:57:12.52Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860623/answer","Biography information for Chloe Smith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860623/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860623/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-03-12","Regulatory Futures Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, with reference to page 8 of his Department's document Regulatory Futures Review, published in January 2018, whether he has received such a report on burdens on smaller regulators.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","131980"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860624","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-03-23","<p>New interconnectors create jobs and contribute to GDP in their construction and ongoing operation. However, we do not hold sufficiently disaggregated data on employment in and GDP contribution from the electricity sector to make a quantitative assessment of the impact of increased interconnection on these points.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2018-03-23T14:32:19.55Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860624/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860624/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860624/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-03-12","Electricity Generation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 1 March 2018 to Question 128954, what assessment he has made of the effect of increased electricity interconnection on (a) net employment in and (b) GDP contribution from the electricity generating sector.","false","Biography information for David T. C. Davies","Monmouth","David T. C. Davies","131981"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860625","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-03-19","<p>The information requested is not collated centrally and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2018-03-19T14:20:47.207Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860625/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860625/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860625/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-03-12","Funeral Payments: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many applications for funeral expenses payments for children under (a) two, (b) five and (c) 18 years have been made in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Anne-Marie Trevelyan","Berwick-upon-Tweed","Mrs Anne-Marie Trevelyan","131982"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860626","Department for Education","false","2018-03-15","<p>We have produced additional analysis of our absence data to look for evidence of period poverty by reviewing variations in absence rates by age, gender and free school meal status. We plan to publish our findings shortly. Information on the department’s pre-announced ad hoc statistics publications can be found here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/department-for-education/about/statistics#contents" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/department-for-education/about/statistics#contents</a>.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-03-15T17:50:18.063Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860626/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860626/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860626/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-03-12","Pupils: Period Poverty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the oral contribution of the Minister for Women of 22 February 2018, Official Report, column 328, when he plans to publish his assessment of the effect of period poverty on school absence rates; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","131983"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860627","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-03-15","<p>As is routine with most high profile appointments, the Commissioner for Public Appointments, reviewed the interview panel report for this role before an announcement was made detailing a preferred candidate. He has confirmed that ‘the report of the panel indicates that the interviews and the assessment were conducted in line with the Government's Governance Code on a fair and equal basis’.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2018-03-15T11:26:58.563Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860627/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860627/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860627/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-03-12","Charity Commission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, whether he consulted the Public Appointments Commissioner on the appointment of the Chair of the Charity Commission before that appointment was publicly announced; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","131984"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860628","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-03-20","<p>​I discussed Western Sahara with the Moroccan Foreign Minister during my visit to Rabat in January. I have also discussed the work of the UN Peacekeeping Mission, MINURSO, and the political process with the UN Secretary-General's Personal Envoy for Western Sahara, former German President Horst Koehler. The UK supports the work of MINURSO, and UN-led efforts to reach a lasting and mutually acceptable solution to the Western Sahara issue that provides for the self-determination of the people of the territory.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-03-20T17:08:54.377Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860628/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860628/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860628/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-03-12","Western Sahara: Peace Keeping Operations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has held with his counterparts in the Government of Morocco on (a) the work of the UN peacekeeping mission to Western Sahara and (b) proposals for a referendum on Saharawi self-determination.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","131985"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860629","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-15","<p>Successive Governments have accepted that the policy of child migration was misguided and deeply flawed.</p><p> </p><p>The Independent Inquiry into Child Sexual Abuse published its Report on the Child Migration Programmes on 1 March. We are considering the content of this report and will provide a formal response in due course.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","131988 ; 131989 ; 131990 ; 131991","2018-03-15T17:31:24.893Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860629/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860629/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860629/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-03-12","Child Sexual Abuse Independent Panel Inquiry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, whether he plans to implement the recommendation of the Independent Inquiry into Child Sexual Abuse's Child Migration Programmes Report on establishing a compensation fund for former child migrants.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","131986"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860630","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2018-03-15","<p>The Government does not comment on specific leak investigations. We take all leaks of information very seriously.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2018-03-15T13:57:13.34Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860630/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860630/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860630/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2018-03-12","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, pursuant to the Answer of 12 March 2018 to Question 130823, whether the Government is carrying out a leak inquiry into reports that a BBC journalist received access to a Market Access Assessment in November 2017.","false","Biography information for Jo Platt","Leigh","Jo Platt","131987"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860631","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-15","<p>Successive Governments have accepted that the policy of child migration was misguided and deeply flawed.</p><p> </p><p>The Independent Inquiry into Child Sexual Abuse published its Report on the Child Migration Programmes on 1 March. We are considering the content of this report and will provide a formal response in due course.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","131986 ; 131989 ; 131990 ; 131991","2018-03-15T17:31:24.97Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860631/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860631/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860631/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-03-12","Child Sexual Abuse Independent Panel Inquiry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, when his Department plans to comply with the recommendation by the Independent Inquiry into Child Sexual Abuse's Child Migration Programmes Report that a government scheme for compensation to former child migrants should be established without delay and operational within 12 months.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","131988"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860632","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-15","<p>Successive Governments have accepted that the policy of child migration was misguided and deeply flawed.</p><p> </p><p>The Independent Inquiry into Child Sexual Abuse published its Report on the Child Migration Programmes on 1 March. We are considering the content of this report and will provide a formal response in due course.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","131986 ; 131988 ; 131990 ; 131991","2018-03-15T17:31:25.047Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860632/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860632/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860632/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-03-12","Child Sexual Abuse Independent Panel Inquiry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, whether he plans to adopt the recommendation by the Independent Inquiry into Child Sexual Abuse's Child Migration Programmes Report that a Government scheme for compensation to former child migrants should apply to all former child migrants covered by previous Child Migration Programmes.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","131989"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860633","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-15","<p>Successive Governments have accepted that the policy of child migration was misguided and deeply flawed.</p><p> </p><p>The Independent Inquiry into Child Sexual Abuse published its Report on the Child Migration Programmes on 1 March. We are considering the content of this report and will provide a formal response in due course.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","131986 ; 131988 ; 131989 ; 131991","2018-03-15T17:31:25.127Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860633/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860633/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860633/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-03-12","Child Sexual Abuse Independent Panel Inquiry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, when he plans to respond to the Independent Inquiry into Child Sexual Abuse's Child Migration Programmes Report.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","131990"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860634","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-15","<p>Successive Governments have accepted that the policy of child migration was misguided and deeply flawed.</p><p> </p><p>The Independent Inquiry into Child Sexual Abuse published its Report on the Child Migration Programmes on 1 March. We are considering the content of this report and will provide a formal response in due course.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","131986 ; 131988 ; 131989 ; 131990","2018-03-15T17:31:25.19Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860634/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860634/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860634/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-03-12","Child Sexual Abuse Independent Panel Inquiry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, whether he plans to adopt the recommendation on page 150 of the Independent Inquiry into Child Sexual Abuse's Child Migration Programmes Report, published in March 2018, that no regard be had to any other payments of compensation that have been made in particular cases to former child migrants by previous Child Migration Programmes.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","131991"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860635","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-03-20","<p>We take seriously the findings of the recent NAO investigation into National Lottery funding for good causes and the trends shown in the Gambling Commission’s report.</p><p>The Department is working closely with the Gambling Commission, Camelot and the Lottery Distributors to achieve the strongest possible National Lottery. Actions include a full strategic review by Camelot of its National Lottery business, alongside other work to encourage participation. Conclusions and findings of these reports have contributed to these discussions, and will continue to be taken into account going forward.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2018-03-20T17:48:38.38Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860635/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860635/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860635/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-03-12","Gambling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment he has made of the implications for his policies of the findings of the (a) National Audit Office Investigation report entitled National Lottery funding for good causes, published in December 2017 and (b) Gambling Commission report entitled Gambling participation in 2017, published in February 2018.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","131992"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860636","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-03-20","<p>The Department meets regularly with Camelot as operator of The National Lottery. Discussions cover topics of interest to both parties and this has included the consultation on prohibiting third party betting on the outcome of non-UK EuroMillions.Details of Ministerial meetings are published quarterly on <a href="http://gov.uk/" target="_blank">gov.uk</a> at this link: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications?departments%5B%5D=department-for-digital-culture-media-sport&amp;publication_type=transparency-data" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications?departments%5B%5D=department-for-digital-culture-media-sport&amp;publication_type=transparency-data</a>&gt;</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2018-03-20T17:51:49.143Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860636/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860636/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860636/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-03-12","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport: Camelot Group","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, on how many occasions he or Ministers or staff of his Department met with Camelot representatives since March 2016; and how many of those meetings dealt with the Consultation on Prohibiting Third Party Betting on the Outcome of non-UK EuroMillions.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","131993"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860637","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-15","<p>Any staff who are compulsorily transferred under Transfer of Undertakings (Protection of Employment) (TUPE) from an National Health Service organisation to a subsidiary company retain their employment terms and conditions, and access to the NHS Pension Scheme, in accordance with HM Treasury’s New Fair Deal policy and TUPE legislation. The Department does not produce national level advice on the recruitment of new non-TUPE staff. It is up to individual trusts to set their own advice when employing staff.</p><p> </p><p>The Department does not hold data on the number of non-TUPE members of staff hired directly by wholly owned subsidiaries of NHS trusts in the last financial year.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","131999 ; 132000","2018-03-15T14:14:30.247Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860637/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860637/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860637/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-03-12","NHS Trusts: Subsidiary Companies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what information his Department holds on the terms that new non-TUPE members of staff were employed on by wholly-owned subsidiaries of NHS trusts in the 2016-17 financial year.","false","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson","131994"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860638","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-15","<p>The Department does not hold information on the records of NHS Pension Scheme members. The NHS Business Service Authority administers the scheme on behalf of the Secretary of State.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2018-03-15T14:16:00.67Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860638/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860638/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860638/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-03-12","NHS: Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what information his Department holds on the access to standard NHS pension arrangements that new non-TUPE staff were granted by wholly-owned subsidiaries of NHS trusts in the 2016-17 financial year.","false","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson","131995"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860639","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-03-19","<p>The Department’s discussions with employers about bereavement or compassionate leave have not referred to agency contracts.</p><p> </p><p>Our manifesto made a commitment that bereaved parents should be able to take some time away from work to grieve for a lost child. To achieve that, the Government is supporting the Parental Bereavement (Leave and Pay) Bill. Consultations with business representatives took place last summer and further consultation will take place this year on the details.</p><p> </p><p>Acas has developed guidance for employers on managing bereavement in the workplace, in conjunction with Cruse Bereavement Care. It recognises the effect that bereavement might have on employees in undertaking their duties, sets out the law in this area and provides guidance on good practice, including having a bereavement policy in place.</p>","Burton","Andrew Griffiths",,"2018-03-19T15:21:25.48Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860639/answer","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860639/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860639/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-03-12","Bereavement Leave","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what discussions his Department has had with employers who use agency contracts on access to bereavement or compassionate leave.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","David Hanson","131996"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860640","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-03-19","<p>The Taylor review into modern employment practices highlighted several areas where the protections of agency workers’ rights could be strengthened.</p><p> </p><p>In response, the Government is currently consulting on the regulation of umbrella companies, and intermediaries; state enforcement of the Agency Worker Regulations; whether “pay between assignments” contracts for agency workers (known as the Swedish derogations) should be repealed; and on the essential information that should be included in a ‘key facts’ summary of an agency worker’s contract.</p><p> </p>","Burton","Andrew Griffiths",,"2018-03-19T15:20:16.357Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860640/answer","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860640/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860640/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-03-12","Temporary Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what recent assessment his Department has made of the effect on the level of workers' rights of people being employed on agency contracts.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","David Hanson","131997"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860641","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-03-19","<p>The Department holds no information on how long agency workers have been employed on contracts for specific periods of time.</p>","Burton","Andrew Griffiths",,"2018-03-19T15:22:38.877Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860641/answer","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860641/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/860641/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-03-12","Temporary Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what recent estimate his Department has made of the number of people who have been employed as agency workers for (a) less than one year, (b) between one and two years and (c) more than two years.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","David Hanson","131998"
