"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858550","Department for Education","false","2018-03-14","<p>The Delivery Support Fund will provide support to the 147 local authorities who submitted a bid for funding. Funding allocations are available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/30-hours-delivery-support-fund-grants-for-local-authorities" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/30-hours-delivery-support-fund-grants-for-local-authorities</a>.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-03-14T17:26:42.75Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858550/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858550/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858550/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-03-09","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much funding each local authority has received from the 30 hours delivery support fund for the Summer 2018 term.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","131805"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858551","Department for Education","false","2018-03-14","<p>The Education and Skills Funding Agency has no powers to compulsory purchase land from either local authorities or private landowners.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","131807","2018-03-14T17:36:41.267Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858551/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858551/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858551/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-03-09","Free Schools","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what powers the Education Skills Funding Agency have to compulsory purchase land from local authorities for free schools.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","131806"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858552","Department for Education","false","2018-03-14","<p>The Education and Skills Funding Agency has no powers to compulsory purchase land from either local authorities or private landowners.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","131806","2018-03-14T17:36:41.327Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858552/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858552/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858552/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-03-09","Free Schools","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what powers the Education Skills Funding Agency has to compulsory purchase land from private land owners for free school sites.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","131807"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858553","Department for Education","false","2018-03-14","<p>Academy trusts proposing to set up a free school have a statutory duty under the Academies Act 2010 to consult on whether to enter into a funding agreement with the Secretary of State to establish a free school. The Act states that trusts should consult “such persons as the trust thinks appropriate”, which should include nearby schools, the local authority, any surrounding local authorities, groups with an interest, the local population, and faith groups. The Secretary of State is also required to complete an assessment of the impact the opening of the school would have on schools in the area, before entering into a funding agreement with the trust.</p><p> </p><p>The Education and Skills Funding Agency works with its contractors and consultants to engage with the local community prior to the submission of a formal planning application, and there is a statutory duty on the local authority, as prescribed in the 2015 Development Management Procedure Order, to consult local communities prior to determination of the application.</p><p> </p><p>The statutory right to challenge the purchase of community assets and other community land for the location of free schools is a local authority matter. If a building or land is registered as an asset of community value, there is a statutory process, under the Localism Act 2011, that a seller of that asset must follow in order to dispose of the land and local authorities would be responsible for taking this forward.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","131809 ; 131810","2018-03-14T17:33:19.94Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858553/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858553/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858553/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-03-09","Free Schools","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether the Education Skills Funding Agency is required to consult local communities on plans for a new free school before planning permission is sought.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","131808"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858554","Department for Education","false","2018-03-14","<p>Academy trusts proposing to set up a free school have a statutory duty under the Academies Act 2010 to consult on whether to enter into a funding agreement with the Secretary of State to establish a free school. The Act states that trusts should consult “such persons as the trust thinks appropriate”, which should include nearby schools, the local authority, any surrounding local authorities, groups with an interest, the local population, and faith groups. The Secretary of State is also required to complete an assessment of the impact the opening of the school would have on schools in the area, before entering into a funding agreement with the trust.</p><p> </p><p>The Education and Skills Funding Agency works with its contractors and consultants to engage with the local community prior to the submission of a formal planning application, and there is a statutory duty on the local authority, as prescribed in the 2015 Development Management Procedure Order, to consult local communities prior to determination of the application.</p><p> </p><p>The statutory right to challenge the purchase of community assets and other community land for the location of free schools is a local authority matter. If a building or land is registered as an asset of community value, there is a statutory process, under the Localism Act 2011, that a seller of that asset must follow in order to dispose of the land and local authorities would be responsible for taking this forward.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","131808 ; 131810","2018-03-14T17:33:20.003Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858554/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858554/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858554/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-03-09","Free Schools","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether people in local communities have the right to object to plans for the establishment of a free school in their area.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","131809"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858555","Department for Education","false","2018-03-14","<p>Academy trusts proposing to set up a free school have a statutory duty under the Academies Act 2010 to consult on whether to enter into a funding agreement with the Secretary of State to establish a free school. The Act states that trusts should consult “such persons as the trust thinks appropriate”, which should include nearby schools, the local authority, any surrounding local authorities, groups with an interest, the local population, and faith groups. The Secretary of State is also required to complete an assessment of the impact the opening of the school would have on schools in the area, before entering into a funding agreement with the trust.</p><p> </p><p>The Education and Skills Funding Agency works with its contractors and consultants to engage with the local community prior to the submission of a formal planning application, and there is a statutory duty on the local authority, as prescribed in the 2015 Development Management Procedure Order, to consult local communities prior to determination of the application.</p><p> </p><p>The statutory right to challenge the purchase of community assets and other community land for the location of free schools is a local authority matter. If a building or land is registered as an asset of community value, there is a statutory process, under the Localism Act 2011, that a seller of that asset must follow in order to dispose of the land and local authorities would be responsible for taking this forward.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","131808 ; 131809","2018-03-14T17:33:20.097Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858555/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858555/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858555/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-03-09","Free Schools","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whethe