"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858617","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-03-14","<p>Homeless Link publishes annual guidance on the Severe Weather Emergency Protocol (SWEP) and it is our expectation that local authorities work together with partners to provide basic emergency accommodation to minimise the risk of harm to individuals when the temperature drops. I recently wrote to local authorities about the guidance on SWEP which can help them protect rough sleepers in their areas at this time.</p><p>Homeless Link also publish the results of a survey of accommodation provided under SWEP or as part of wider winter provision, which you can find on their website. <a href="https://www.homeless.org.uk/sites/default/files/site-attachments/SWEP%20survey%20report%202016-17.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.homeless.org.uk/sites/default/files/site-attachments/SWEP%20survey%20report%202016-17.pdf</a></p><p>No one should ever have to sleep rough. That is why we are aiming to halve rough sleeping by 2022 and eliminate it altogether by 2027. A new Rough Sleeping and Homelessness Reduction Taskforce brings together relevant ministers from across Government, and will drive forward the implementation of a cross-Government strategy to tackle this issue. They are supported by an Advisory Panel made up of experts from local government and the homelessness sector.</p><p> </p>","South Derbyshire","Mrs Heather Wheeler",,"2018-03-14T17:12:45.357Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858617/answer","Biography information for Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858617/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858617/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-03-09","Homelessness: Weather","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the adequacy of the level of (a) provision, (b) availability and (c) funding for shelters for (i) homeless people and (ii) rough sleepers during periods of extremely cold weather; and what comparative assessment he has made of the level of (A) provision and (B) demand for such services.","false","Biography information for Mike Amesbury","Weaver Vale","Mike Amesbury","131872"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858618","Department for Education","false","2018-03-20","<p>The Department has not conducted an assessment and does not hold statistics about the effect of school police liaison officers on pupils’ behaviour, truancy rates and youth crime rates in areas where such officers are deployed.</p><p> </p><p>It is a matter for local police forces to decide their strategy for working with schools. However, we do recognise that police working with schools through initiatives such as the Safer School Partnerships are a proven method for achieving effective joint working between schools and police.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-03-20T17:28:27.967Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858618/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858618/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858618/answer","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858618/answer/previousversion/48391","Biography information for Nick Gibb","60","Education","Education","2018-03-09","Schools: Police","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment he has made of the effect of school police liaison officers on (a) pupil's behaviour, (b) truancy rates and (c) youth crime rates in areas where such officers are deployed.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","131873"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858619","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-03-14","<p>It will take some time to gather the information required to answer the hon. Member's question and I will write to him shortly.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2018-03-14T16:42:44.96Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858619/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858619/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858619/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-03-09","Armed Forces: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many armed forces personnel in specialist positions have been informed they are no longer eligible for specialist pay and are required to repay it.","false","Biography information for Alex Sobel","Leeds North West","Alex Sobel","131874"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858620","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-14","<p>The Department does not collect this data.</p><p> </p><p>There were over 2,553 more full time equivalent midwives working in the National Health Service in November 2017, an increase of 13.1% compared to 2010.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2018-03-14T11:59:10.597Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858620/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858620/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858620/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-03-09","Midwives: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what the attrition rate was for students on midwifery courses in each of the last five completed cohorts for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","131875"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858621","Department for Education","false","2018-03-14","<p>The department has not made constituency-level forecasts of the number of pupils that will be entitled to free school meals under the new criteria. At a national level, it is estimated that by 2022 around 50,000 more children will benefit from a free school meal compared to the previous benefits system.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","131788","2018-03-14T17:15:51.5Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858621/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858621/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858621/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-03-09","Free School Meals: Leeds North West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate he has made of the number of pupils entitled to free school meals in the Leeds North West constituency after recent changes to the  threshold for free school meals eligibility under universal credit.","false","Biography information for Alex Sobel","Leeds North West","Alex Sobel","131876"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858622","Department for Education","false","2018-03-14","<p>As previously announced, the Government will review the GCSE physical education activity list in autumn 2018, following the first examinations this summer. The Department will agree this process with the examination boards and Ofqual and announce details closer to the time. This review will apply to published subject content with which all examination boards are required to comply. The Department would not expect this to lead to changes in the marking criteria.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-03-14T17:04:13.353Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858622/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858622/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858622/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-03-09","Physical Education: GCSE","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether he plans to review the AQA GCSE Physical Education framework to offer a wider variety of options in the marking criteria.","false","Biography information for Alex Sobel","Leeds North West","Alex Sobel","131877"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858623","Treasury","false","2018-03-15","<p>The government believes that the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA), as the UK’s independent conduct regulator for the financial services industry, is best placed to lead the discussion on the merits of a duty of a care for financial services providers.</p><p> </p><p>The FCA have committed to issuing a Discussion Paper on a duty of care later this year. The Paper will invite contributions from all interested parties on the case for and against a duty of care, what form such a provision might take, and consequential issues arising from adopting it. This will be an open process designed to gather views.</p><p> </p><p>In this context, the government welcomes the FCA’s continued commitment to this debate, and we do not think an amendment to the Financial Guidance and Claims Bill would be appropriate.</p><p> </p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2018-03-15T15:44:53.743Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858623/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858623/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858623/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-03-09","Financial Services: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will bring forward legislative proposals on the duty of care within the Financial Guidance and Claims Bill.","false","Biography information for Alex Sobel","Leeds North West","Alex Sobel","131878"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858624","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-03-15","<p>A Child Maintenance liability is calculated using the paying parent’s gross income obtained directly from HMRC. The receiving parent’s income is not considered. The paying parent is required to inform the Service of any changes in personal financial circumstances which would alter the maintenance liability. There are no plans to review this requirement.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse","131882","2018-03-15T14:19:32.743Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858624/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858624/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858624/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-03-09","Children: Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether he plans to review the requirements for (a) the carer parent and (b) the absent parent to inform the Child Maintenance Service of personal financial changes.","false","Biography information for Hywel Williams","Arfon","Hywel Williams","131879"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858625","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-03-14","<p>Enforcement action within the Child Maintenance Service collects money for the benefit of children and is only used against non-paying parents, rather than against receiving parents.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2018-03-14T17:36:33.07Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858625/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858625/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858625/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-03-09","Children: Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the comparative rate of enforcement action between carer and absent parents using the Child Maintenance Service.","false","Biography information for Hywel Williams","Arfon","Hywel Williams","131880"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858626","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-03-14","<p>When measuring the efficacy of the Child Maintenance Service, we collect data on rate of compliance. These figures are published quarterly in table 6 of the Child Maintenance Service experimental statistics data tables, which can be found here:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/684262/tables-child-maintenance-service-august-2013-to-december-2017.ods" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/684262/tables-child-maintenance-service-august-2013-to-december-2017.ods</a></p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2018-03-14T17:34:39.31Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858626/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858626/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858626/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-03-09","Children: Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the efficacy of the Child Maintenance Service to date.","false","Biography information for Hywel Williams","Arfon","Hywel Williams","131881"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858627","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-03-15","<p>A Child Maintenance liability is calculated using the paying parent’s gross income obtained directly from HMRC. The receiving parent’s income is not considered. The paying parent is required to inform the Service of any changes in personal financial circumstances which would alter the maintenance liability. There are no plans to review this requirement.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse","131879","2018-03-15T14:19:32.807Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858627/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858627/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858627/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-03-09","Children: Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what information on changes in financial circumstances are required from each party within a Child Maintenance Support agreement.","false","Biography information for Hywel Williams","Arfon","Hywel Williams","131882"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858628","Cabinet Office","false","2018-03-26","<p>The Policy Profession has developed a set of established professional standards, against which we have developed a range of learning activities. One area of focus, raised in the What Works report, has been on developing and testing an approach that uses experienced policy (and analytical) colleagues to assess junior colleagues’ practical experience against the standards. These standards were agreed in December 2017, having been reviewed and improved after an initial small scale pilot assessments on 19 people across 6 departments to test them out. Broader pilots are due to start from May 2018.</p><p>In 2015 we launched a 2 year <a href="http://www.lse.ac.uk/school-of-public-policy/EMPP" target="_blank">Executive Masters in Public Policy</a> with London School of Economics (pitched as Senior Civil Servants at the first level, SCS1) which the first cohort of 28 passed in 2017.</p>","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden",,"2018-03-26T14:53:22.78Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858628/answer","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858628/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/858628/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-03-09","Civil Servants: Qualifications","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, with reference to page 35 of his Department's report, The What Works Network: Five years on, what formal accreditation civil servants will achieve and which roles and grades of civil servant will participate.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","131883"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/857659","Church Commissioners","false","2018-03-08","<p>The Church Commissioners provide financial and administrative support to cathedrals and dioceses. It is up to each self-governing church or cathedral to raise funds for development projects, and the National Church Institutions provide advice and support.</p><p>The changing priorities and declining budget of the Heritage Lottery Fund is a matter of concern, as this is where much fundraising money comes from; officers at national level continue to work with the Heritage Lottery Fund on the specific issues churches face. The HLF is currently reviewing its strategic priorities and I would encourage all Hon. members to consider sending in a response, making the importance of churches as community assets clear.</p><p>The Church of England has been in discussions with the Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport and HM Treasury about the current underspend of the Listed Places of Worship Grant Scheme, realocating the underspend would enable the Church to deliver a number of the recommendations in the Taylor Review.</p><p> </p>","Meriden","Dame Caroline Spelman",,"2018-03-08T14:53:55.707Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/857659/answer","Biography information for Dame Caroline Spelman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/857659/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/857659/answer",,,,,"9","Church Commissioners","Church Commissioners","2018-03-08","Churches: Infrastructure","1","House of Commons","To ask the right hon. Member for Meriden, representing the Church Commissioners, what funding is available for church infrastructure projects.","false","Biography information for Robert Halfon","Harlow","Robert Halfon","904239"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/857662","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-03-12","<p>Hill farmers play an important role in the maintenance of traditional upland landscapes providing both environmental and cultural benefits. The Government’s consultation document ‘Health and Harmony: the future for food, farming and the environment in a green Brexit’ makes clear that upland areas have the potential to benefit from the proposed new environmental land management schemes in England, given the nature of their landscapes and the public goods that they deliver.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-03-12T12:15:39.6Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/857662/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/857662/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/857662/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-03-08","Hill Farming","1","House of Commons","If he will bring forward legislative proposals to support hill farmers after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Chris Davies","Brecon and Radnorshire","Chris Davies","904250"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/857663","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-03-14","<p>Local authorities already have powers to create clean air zones. None currently exist but proposals for them are being drawn up by some local authorities.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2018-03-14T17:53:44.667Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/857663/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/857663/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/857663/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-03-08","Clean Air Zones","1","House of Commons","Whether he plans to expand clean air zones.","false","Biography information for Stephen Morgan","Portsmouth South","Stephen Morgan","904261"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/857665","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-03-14","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the replies previously given on 6 March 2018, PQs 129872, 129873, 129874 and 129875. Whilst it is not possible to prevent all oil spills into the river, in this incident, the Environment Agency have traced the waste oil to a potential polluter, details of which cannot currently be released due to the ongoing investigation. In previous incidents where oil pollution was not traced to a particular source, the Environment Agency carried out pollution prevention visits at industrial premises which drain to the Pymmes Brook.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2018-03-14T16:07:32.3Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/857665/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/857665/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/857665/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-03-08","River Lea: Pollution Control","1","House of Commons","What assessment he has made of the effectiveness of the Environment Agency in preventing oil spills in the River Lea; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","904264"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/857706","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-03-13","<p>The Ministry of Defence (MOD) approach to acquisition is to carefully assess the choices available to achieve best value for money while meeting the needs of the UK Armed Forces. This is sometimes achieved through competition, sometimes through single source arrangements, and sometimes through collaboration, which itself may involve elements of competition.</p><p>International organisations such as the Organisation for Joint Armament Cooperation (OCCAR) will establish value for money in a similar way to the UK MOD. This can include establishing prices via competitions. They will also have similar provisions in place to those under the UK's Single Source Contract Regulations (SSCR), which includes detailed visibility of the breakdown of costs.</p><p>The MOD seeks to ensure value for money in single source procurement through the provisions of the Defence Reform Act 2014 and the associated SSCR. Parliament enacted this legislation specifically to address some of the difficulties the MOD had previously faced in assuring value for money when undertaking single source procurement. This approach has already significantly strengthened the MOD's ability to secure value for money through single source procurement.</p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb",,"2018-03-13T15:51:55.063Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/857706/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/857706/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/857706/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-03-08","Defence: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that equipment purchased via the Organisation for Joint Armament Cooperation or single source procurement provides value for money.","false","Biography information for Gerald Jones","Merthyr Tydfil and Rhymney","Gerald Jones","131607"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/857707","Department for Education","false","2018-03-13","<p>As set out in the Ofsted statistical first release (SFR) data<sup><sup>[1]</sup></sup> as at 31 August 2017 and also Pupils data<sup><sup>[2]</sup></sup>, there were 5,682 eligible pupils for free school meals, who attended a primary school in Nottinghamshire of which, 79 per cent were in schools rated by Ofsted as Good; and eight per cent were in schools rated by Ofsted as Outstanding.</p><p> </p><p>There were 500,386 eligible pupils for free school meals, who attended a primary school in England of which, 73 per cent were in schools rated by Ofsted as Good; and 15 per cent were in schools rated by Ofsted as Outstanding.</p><p> </p><p>[1] Ofsted - <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/maintained-schools-and-academies-inspections-and-outcomes-as-at-31-august-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/maintained-schools-and-academies-inspections-and-outcomes-as-at-31-august-2017</a>.</p><p> </p><p>[2] Pupils Data - <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/schools-pupils-and-their-characteristics-january-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/schools-pupils-and-their-characteristics-january-2017</a>.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-03-13T15:56:52.243Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/857707/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/857707/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/857707/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-03-08","Pupils: Disadvantaged","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what proportion of primary school pupils eligible for free school meals in (a) Nottinghamshire and b) England attend a school rated as (i) good or (ii) outstanding by Ofsted.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","131608"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/857708","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-03-13","<p>The Sanctions and Anti-Money Laundering Bill will come into force on a day appointed by the Secretary of State, who may choose to commence different clauses on different days. This will ensure that there is no gap when the anti-money laundering and sanctions regimes in force now, under the EU, are transferred to the new UK framework. The exact timetable required will be dependent on the ongoing withdrawal negotiations with the EU.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2018-03-13T17:31:43.237Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/857708/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/857708/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/857708/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-03-08","Money Laundering and Sanctions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what the timetable is for implementing the Government's new anti-money laundering and sanctions regime.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","131609"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/857709","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-03-14","<p>The Government set out its policy on neonicotinoids on 09 November: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/environment-secretary-backs-further-restrictions-on-neonicotinoid-pesticides" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/news/environment-secretary-backs-further-restrictions-on-neonicotinoid-pesticides</a></p><p> </p><p>The Government supports further restrictions on neonicotinoids, based on the latest evidence.</p><p> </p><p>A number of EU Member States indicated that they wished to see the outputs of the European Food safety Authority (EFSA) work before reaching a position on neonicotinoids. Now the EFSA work is complete, negotiations on this issue should restart in the coming months.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-03-14T12:02:22.913Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/857709/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/857709/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/857709/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-03-08","Neonicotinoids: EU Action","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 7 February 2018 to Question 126415, and with reference to the conclusion published on 28 February 2018 from the European Food Safety Authority on the risk to wild bees and honeybees from the use of neonicotinoid pesticides, if he will set out the Government's policy on the banning of neonicotinoids; by what date the Government is asking for negotiations to restart on the matter of neonicotinoids; if he will take steps to ban neonicotinoids in the UK in the event of undue time being taken at EU level on that matter; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","131610"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/857710","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-13","<p>Data on the number of men who were diagnosed late and died from prostate cancer are not available in the format requested.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-03-13T13:42:07.3Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/857710/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/857710/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/857710/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-03-08","Prostate Cancer: Halton","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, whether his Department collects information on the number of men who (a) were diagnosed late for and (b) died from prostate cancer by GP surgery in Halton constituency.","false","Biography information for Derek Twigg","Halton","Derek Twigg","131611"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/857711","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-03-13","<p>The information requested is not collated centrally and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2018-03-13T15:00:19.743Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/857711/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/857711/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/857711/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-03-08","State Retirement Pensions: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 5 March 2018 to Question 130479, on state retirement: pensions, how many complaints the Independent Case Examiners Office has received in total by constituency.","false","Biography information for Derek Twigg","Halton","Derek Twigg","131612"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/857712","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-03-19","<p>The Government’s Inclusion Health programme published a number of resources from 2013 to 2016 on key issues affecting Gypsies, Travellers and Roma people. The reports were largely developed with the participation of Gypsy, Traveller and Roma stakeholders and health professionals. These included guidance on planning and commissioning inclusive services and a report on the impact of insecure accommodation and the living environment on Gypsies’ and Travellers’ health.</p><p>On 5 March 2018, the Government launched a consultation on proposed revisions to the National Planning Policy Framework. The consultation asks whether any changes should be made to the Planning Policy for Traveller Sites as a result of the proposed changes to the Framework, and if so, what these changes should be. We welcome views on the consultation, which closes on 10 May 2018 and can be accessed here <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/draft-revised-national-planning-policy-framework" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/draft-revised-national-planning-policy-framework</a></p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2018-03-19T15:59:59.467Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/857712/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/857712/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/857712/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-03-08","Gypsies and Travellers: Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, with reference to the report of the Ministerial working group on tackling inequalities experienced by Gypsies and Travellers, published in April 2012, what recent discussions he has had with the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care on progress in promoting improved health outcomes for Gypsy, Roma and Travelling communities through the planning system; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","131613"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/857713","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-03-15","<p>On 11 November 2014 in response to a Question UIN HL2504 from Lord Avebury, Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon provided a summary of progress on the 28 commitments made by the Ministerial Working Group on tackling inequalities experienced by Gypsies and Travellers.</p><p>The Government is concerned about the inequalities experienced by Gypsy, Roma and Traveller communities and maintains close contact with representative groups. Ministers in the Ministry of Housing, Communities &amp; Local Government, the Department for Education and the Department of Health and Social Care are committed to working together to tackle the poor life chances of these groups, and will be running a series of projects to improve outcomes for Gypsy, Roma and Traveller communities in the areas of educational attainment, health and social integration through a fund which will concentrate on localised approaches that have been proved to deliver positive results. We intend to announce successful projects before April.</p>","South Derbyshire","Mrs Heather Wheeler",,"2018-03-15T16:19:58.837Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/857713/answer","Biography information for Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/857713/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/857713/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-03-08","Travellers: Equality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, with reference to the report of the Ministerial working group on tackling inequalities experienced by Gypsies and Travellers, published in April 2012, what recent steps his Department has taken to support Gypsy and Traveller representative groups showcase small private sites that are well presented and maintained.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","131614"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/857714","Treasury","false","2018-03-16","<p>The Government is committed to ensuring that individuals, regardless of their background or income, have access to useful and affordable financial products and services. The Equality Act 2010 protects all individuals, including Gypsies and Travellers, against racial and other forms of discrimination.</p><p> </p><p>The Payment Accounts Regulations 2015 require the nine largest personal current account providers in the UK to offer fee-free basic bank accounts to customers who do not have a bank account or who are ineligible for a bank’s standard current account. The regulations also state that when a customer applies for an account, firms must not discriminate by reason of the customer’s place of residence, and that the conditions applicable to holding a basic bank account must not be discriminatory.</p><p> </p><p>In order to open a basic bank account, firms will need to verify their customers’ identities, which generally includes verifying their addresses. While the way in which firms choose to do this is not stipulated in law or by the regulator, firms are assisted in making such policies through industry produced guidance notes. For the financial institutions, these are the Joint Money Laundering Steering Group (JMLSG) guidance notes.</p><p> </p><p>The JMLSG guidance notes acknowledge that if Travellers are not able to produce standard identification evidence, and if verification of address is necessary, a check with the local authority, which has to register travellers’ sites, may sometimes be helpful.</p><p> </p><p>More widely, the Government has also committed to establish a Financial Inclusion Policy Forum, which will provide leadership and ensure collaboration across government and with the sector in tackling financial exclusion.</p><p> </p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2018-03-16T11:26:18.763Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/857714/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/857714/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/857714/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-03-08","Bank Services: Travellers","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps he has taken to encourage the banking sector to improve financial inclusion for Gypsies and Travellers.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","131615"
